      "component": "Maladaptive Strategies",
      "item": "Substance Use: I drink alcohol, take medication or use drugs",
      "explanation": "Directly contradicts the 'Olfactory (Alcohol): Alcohol smell' trigger item. A patient with alcohol as a trauma trigger would typically avoid alcohol use, not report active substance use involving alcohol. This creates an implausible clinical picture for a suicide trauma."
    },
    {
      "component": "Memory",
      "item": "Photographic Recall: Remembering what happened during the frightening event is just like looking at photographs of it in my mind.",
      "explanation": "Inconsistent with suicide trauma type. Suicide typically involves discovering or witnessing the aftermath, not directly observing the traumatic event as it occurs. Photographic recall implies visual witnessing of the event itself, which is clinically implausible for most suicide traumas."
    },
    {
      "component": "Memory",
      "item": "Bodily Reenactment: When memories come to mind of what happened, I feel my body is in the same position as when the frightening event occurred.",
      "explanation": "Clinically implausible for suicide trauma. Bodily reenactment typically occurs with direct physical threat or assault. For a suicide trauma (likely discovering a body or aftermath), there is no specific bodily position to reenact that would be meaningfully connected to the trauma."
    }
  ]
}
